{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}} [[File:Hywind.jpg|thumb|The world’s first full-scale floating wind turbine, Hywind, being assembled in the Åmøy Fjord near [[Stavanger]], [[Norway]] in 2009, before deployment in the [[North Sea]]]] A '''floating wind turbine''' is an [[offshore wind power|offshore]] [[wind turbine]] mounted on a floating structure that allows the turbine to generate [[electricity]] in water depths where fixed-foundation turbines are not feasible.<ref name=ge20110913/> Floating wind farms have the potential to significantly increase the sea area available for offshore wind farms, especially in countries with limited shallow waters, such as Japan. Locating wind farms farther offshore can also reduce [[visual pollution]],<ref name=ge20110913>{{cite news|last=Laskow|first=Sarah|title=Hope Floats for a New Generation of Deep-Water Wind Farms|url=http://www.good.is/post/hope-floats-for-a-new-generation-of-deep-water-wind-farms/|accessdate=12 October 2011|newspaper=Good Environment|date=13 September 2011}}</ref> provide better accommodation for fishing and [[shipping lane]]s,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyfinance.com/2009/09/09/the-worlds-first-floating-wind-turbine-goes-on-line-in-norway/|title=The world's first floating wind turbine goes on line in Norway|author=[http://www.dailyfinance.com/bloggers/mark-svenvold/ Mark Svenvold]|date=9 September 2009|accessdate=20 October 2009|publisher=DailyFinance.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucsusa.org/clean_energy/technology_and_impacts/impacts/farming-the-wind-wind-power.html|title=Farming the Wind: Wind Power and Agriculture|author=[[Union of Concerned Scientists]]|date=15 July 2003|accessdate=20 October 2009|quote=<!-- This citation added to support the removal of unsupported statements regarding competition between wind turbines and agriculture -->}}</ref> and reach stronger and more consistent winds.<ref name="Musial2003"/>
Commercial floating wind turbines are mostly at the early phase of development, with several single turbine prototypes having been installed since 2007. As of 2018, the only operational floating wind farm is Hywind Scotland, developed by [[Statoil]] and commissioned in October 2017. The farm has 5 floating turbines with a total capacity of 30 MW.<ref name="cleantechnica.com">{{cite web|title=Hywind Scotland, World's First Floating Wind Farm, Performing Better Than Expected {{!}} CleanTechnica|url=https://cleantechnica.com/2018/02/16/hywind-scotland-worlds-first-floating-wind-farm-performing-better-expected/|website=cleantechnica.com|accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref>
==History== [[File:VolturnUS 1-8 in Castine ME.jpg|thumb|University of Maine's [[VolturnUS (floating wind turbine)|VolturnUS 1:8]] was the first grid-connected offshore wind turbine in the Americas.<ref name="cbsnews.com">{{Citation|title=Nation's first floating wind turbine launched|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/videos/nations-first-floating-wind-turbine-launched/|accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref>]] [[File:Agucadoura WindFloat Prototype.jpg|thumb|The world's second full-scale floating wind turbine (and first to be installed without the use of heavy-lift vessels), WindFloat, operating at rated capacity (2&nbsp;MW) approximately 5&nbsp;km offshore of [[Aguçadoura]], Portugal]] The concept for large-scale offshore floating wind turbines was introduced by Professor William E. Heronemus at the [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]] in 1972. It was not until the mid 1990s, after the commercial wind industry was well established, that the topic was taken up again by the mainstream research community.<ref name="Musial2003">{{cite journal|last=Musial|first=W.|author2=S. Butterfield|author3=A. Boone|title=Feasibility of Floating Platform Systems for Wind Turbines|journal=NREL preprint|issue=NREL/CP-500-34874|page=14|publisher=[[National Renewable Energy Laboratory|NREL]]|date=November 2003|url=http://www.osti.gov/bridge/servlets/purl/15005820-0aqZAv/native/15005820.pdf|accessdate=10 September 2009}}</ref> <!--Worldwide deep-water wind resources are extremely abundant in [[subsea]] areas with depths up to 600 metres, which are thought to best facilitate [[electric power transmission|transmission]] of the [[Submarine power cable|generated electric power]] to shore communities.<ref name="Musial2003"/> Two-thirds of the [[North Sea]] is between 50 and 220 metres deep.<ref>KASPER BRØNDGAARD ANDERSEN. "[http://energiwatch.dk/Energinyt/Politik___Markeder/article5750337.ece Industrien: Vindmøller skal ud, hvor de ikke kan bunde]" ''EnergiWatch'', 25 July 2013. Accessed: 17 October 2013</ref> -->
Blue H Technologies of the [[Netherlands]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eti.co.uk/programmes/offshore-wind/deep-water|title=Deep Water - The ETI|date=18 July 2018|website=The ETI}}</ref> deployed the first 80-kW floating wind turbine<ref name=iet20101018>[http://kn.theiet.org/magazine/issues/1016/deep-water-turbines-1016.cfm Deep water wind turbines], ''[[The Institution of Engineering and Technology]]'', 18 October 2010, accessed 6 November 2011 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101126164144/http://kn.theiet.org/magazine/issues/1016/deep-water-turbines-1016.cfm |date=26 November 2010 }}</ref> {{convert|21.3|km|mi}} off the coast of [[Apulia]], [[Italy]] in December 2007. The prototype was installed in waters 113 m deep in order to gather test data on wind and sea conditions, and was decommissioned at the end of 2008.{{citation needed|date=May 2012}} The turbine utilized a [[tension-leg platform]] design and a two-bladed turbine.{{Citation needed|date=October 2011}}
[[File:Floating loose mooring catenary plain.svg|thumb|A single floating cylindrical [[spar buoy]] moored by [[Catenary#Anchoring of marine vessels|catenary]] cables. Hywind uses a ''ballasted catenary'' layout that adds 60 tonne weights hanging from the midpoint of each anchor cable to provide additional tension.]] The first large-capacity, 2.3-megawatt floating wind turbine was Hywind,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statoil.com/en/TechnologyInnovation/NewEnergy/RenewablePowerProduction/Offshore/Hywind/Pages/HywindPuttingWindPowerToTheTest.aspx|title=Technology - Technology and innovation - equinor.com|website=www.statoil.com}}</ref> which became operational in the [[North Sea]] near [[Norway]] in September 2009.<ref name=BBC20090908>{{Cite journal|title=Floating challenge for offshore wind turbine|author=Madslien, Jorn|publisher=BBC News|date=8 September 2009|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/8235456.stm|accessdate=14 September 2009}}</ref><ref name="BBC200906">{{cite news|title=Floating wind turbine launched|author=Madslien, Jorn|publisher=BBC News|date=5 June 2009|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/8085551.stm |accessdate=14 September 2009}}</ref> The turbine was constructed by [[Siemens Wind Power]] and mounted on a floating tower with a 100 m deep draft, with a float tower constructed by [[Technip]].
After assembly in the calmer waters of Åmøy Fjord near [[Stavanger|Stavanger, Norway]], the 120 m tall tower was towed 10&nbsp;km offshore into 220 m deep water, 10&nbsp;km southwest of [[Karmøy]], on 6 June 2009 for a two-year test deployment.<ref name="Patel2009"/> Alexandra Beck Gjorv of Statoil said, "[The experiment] should help move offshore wind farms out of sight … The global market for such turbines is potentially enormous, depending on how low we can press costs."<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.upi.com/Business_News/2009/06/06/First-offshore-wind-turbine-goes-to-sea/UPI-40901244312888/ |title=First offshore wind turbine goes to sea|date=6 June 2009|publisher=UPI |accessdate=7 June 2009}}</ref> Hywind, owned by [[Statoil]],<ref name="Patel2009"/> cost 400 million kroner (around [[US$]]62 million) to build and deploy.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.ntm.nickles.com/issues/story.aspx?aid=1000340202|title=Statoil Draws On Offshore Oil Expertise To Develop World's First Floating Wind Turbine|date=8 September 2009|accessdate=21 October 2009|publisher=NewTechnology magazine}}{{dead link|date=October 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.energycurrent.com/index.php?id=3&storyid=18144 |title=Maine task force to identify offshore wind energy sites|last=Turker|first=Tux|date=19 May 2009|publisher=Energy Current|accessdate=7 June 2009}}{{Dead link|date=September 2009}}</ref> The {{convert|13|km|mi|adj=on}} long [[submarine power cable|submarine power transmission cable]] was installed in July 2009 and system test including rotor blades and initial power transmission was conducted shortly thereafter.<ref name="Donovan200908">{{cite news|last=Donovan|first=Matthew|title=Subsea cable installed at Hywind project|publisher=Energy Current|date=11 August 2009|url= http://www.energycurrent.com/index.php?id=3&storyid=19929 |accessdate=2 September 2009}}{{Dead link|date=September 2009}}</ref> The installation was expected to generate about 9 [[gigawatt hour|GW·h]] of electricity annually.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.regjeringen.no/en/dep/oed/whats-new/speeches-and-articles/the_minister/speeches-and-articles-by-the-minister-of/2009/opening-of-hywind--the-worlds-first-full.html?id=576658 |title=Speech: Opening of Hywind – the world’s first full-scale floating wind turbine|author=[[Terje Riis-Johansen]], Minister of Petroleum and Energy, Norway|date=9 October 2009|accessdate=21 October 2009|publisher=Norway Ministry of Petroleum and Energy}}</ref> In 2010 it survived 11 meter waves with seemingly no wear.<ref>Nilsen, Jannicke. [http://www.tu.no/industri/article284447.ece Statoil wants Hywind in Japan] ''[[Teknisk Ukeblad]]'', 4 April 2011. Accessed: 4 April 2011</ref> By 2016, the turbine had produced 50 GWh; an overall [[capacity factor]] of 41%.<ref name=waterin/>{{update after|2018|8|3}}<!-- is it still operational in 2018? -->
In October 2011, WindFloat prototype was installed 4&nbsp;km offshore of Aguçadoura, Portugal by Principle Power in approximately 45&nbsp;m of water (previously the [[Aguçadoura Wave Farm]] site). The WindFloat was fitted with a Vestas V80 2.0-MW offshore wind turbine and grid connected. The installation was the first offshore wind turbine to be deployed without the use of any offshore heavy lift vessels as the turbine was fully commissioned onshore prior to the unit's being towed offshore. This is the first offshore wind turbine installed in open Atlantic waters, and the first to employ a semi-submersible type floating foundation.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://principlepowerinc.com/news/press_PPI_WF_deployment.html | title= First WindFloat Successfully Deployed Offshore|date=30 November 2011 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311201309/http://www.principlepowerinc.com/news/press_PPI_WF_deployment.html | archivedate=11 March 2012}}</ref>{{Better source|date=March 2012}}
[[SeaTwirl]] deployed its first floating grid connected wind turbine off the coast of Sweden in August 2011. It was tested and decommissioned.<ref name=ewea2011>Justin Wilkes et al. [http://www.ewea.org/fileadmin/ewea_documents/documents/publications/statistics/EWEA_stats_offshore_2011_02.pdf The European offshore wind industry key 2011 trends and statistics] p5 ''[[European Wind Energy Association]]'', January 2012. Accessed: 26 March 2012</ref> The design intended to store energy in a [[flywheel]], thus, energy could be produced even after the wind stopped blowing.<ref name=Chalmers>{{cite web|url=http://www.chalmers.se/ap/SV/utbildning/examensarbeten/lediga-kandidatarbeten/sea-twirl-new-type-off|title=Teknisk fysik|publisher=Chalmers.se|accessdate=2 December 2013}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
In June 2013, the [[University of Maine]] deployed the VolturnUS 1:8, a {{convert|65|foot|m}} tall floating turbine prototype that is 1:8th the scale of a 6-megawatt (MW), {{convert|450|foot|m}} rotor diameter design.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bangordailynews.com/video/volturnus-18-windturbine-launched/|title=VolturnUS 1:8 windturbine launches in 2013|access-date=5 July 2016}}</ref> VolturnUS 1:8 was the first grid-connected offshore wind turbine deployed in the Americas. The VolturnUS design utilizes a concrete semi-submersible floating hull and a composite materials tower designed to reduce both capital and Operation & Maintenance costs, and to allow local manufacturing. The technology was the result of collaborative research and development conducted by the University of Maine-led DeepCwind Consortium.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://composites.umaine.edu/our-research/offshore-wind/deepcwind-consortium/|title=DeepCwind Consortium {{!}} Advanced Structures & Composites Center {{!}} University of Maine|website=composites.umaine.edu|access-date=5 July 2016}}</ref>{{update after|2018|8|3}}
In 2013, Statoil pulled out of the $120&nbsp;million project of four 3-MW turbines floating in 140 m depth of water near [[Boothbay Harbor, Maine]] citing change in legislation,<ref>Tux Turkel. "[http://www.pressherald.com/news/Statoil_pulling_out_of_Maine_.html Statoil leaving Maine for more certain climate (page 1)]" [http://www.pressherald.com/news/Statoil_pulling_out_of_Maine_.html?pagenum=2 Page 2] ''[[Portland Press Herald]]'', 15 October 2013. Accessed: 17 October 2013</ref><ref>Sue Mello. "[http://www.boothbayregister.com/article/statoil-pulls-out/22363 Statoil pulls out]" ''Boothbay Register'', 15 October 2013. Accessed: 17 October 2013</ref><ref>Whit Richardson. "[http://bangordailynews.com/2013/10/15/business/statoil-to-quit-work-on-offshore-wind-project-in-maine/ Statoil to quit work on $120 million offshore wind project in Maine]" ''[[Bangor Daily News]]'', 15 October 2013. Accessed: 17 October 2013</ref> and focused on their five 6-MW turbines in Scotland instead, where the average wind speed is 10&nbsp;m/s and the water depth is 100 m.<ref>THOMAS BO CHRISTENSEN. "[http://energiwatch.dk/Energinyt/Renewables/article6107498.ece Statoils amerikanske flydemøller blæst omkuld]" ''EnergiWatch'', 15 October 2013. Accessed: 17 October 2013</ref><ref>"[http://www.4coffshore.com/windfarms/hywind-2-demonstration-(uk)-united-kingdom-uk76.html Hywind 2 Demonstration (UK) 30 MW]", ''4C''. Accessed: 17 October 2013</ref><ref>Simon Hadley. "[http://www.ukoffshorewind.com/news/first-floating-wind-farm-could-be-in-scottish-waters.aspx Statoil floats Scottish plans] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022124045/http://www.ukoffshorewind.com/news/first-floating-wind-farm-could-be-in-scottish-waters.aspx |date=22 October 2013 }}" ''UK offshore wind''. Accessed: 17 October 2013</ref>
In 2015, Statoil received permission to install ''Hywind Scotland'', a 30 MW floating wind farm {{convert|18|mi|km}} off [[Peterhead]] using 5 Hywind turbines. Statoil also plans to test a 1 MWh lithium-ion battery system (called Batwind) with the farm. Hywind Scotland was commissioned in October 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/business/business-energy/statoil-pilot-floating-wind-farm-6749984|title=Statoil to pilot floating wind farm scheme offshore Peterhead|first=Scott|last=McCulloch|date=2 November 2015|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-business-34694463|title=Floating wind farm to be UK first|date=2 November 2015|publisher=|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{youtube|PpMOP5ogWWA}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.4coffshore.com/windfarms/hywind-scotland-pilot-park-united-kingdom-uk76.html|title=Hywind Scotland Pilot Park - 4C Offshore|website=www.4coffshore.com}}</ref><ref>Nilsen, Jannicke. [http://www.tu.no/artikler/statoil-utvikler-eget-batteri-system-for-lagring-av-vindkraft/345712 Statoil utvikler eget batteri-system for lagring av vindkraft] ''[[Teknisk Ukeblad]]'', 21 March 2016. Accessed: 21 March 2016</ref> becoming the first commercial floating wind farm in operation. Construction of the NOK 2 billion (£152m) project started in 2016 in Spain, Norway and Scotland. The turbines were assembled at [[Stord]] in Norway in summer 2017 using the [[Saipem 7000]] floating crane, and the finished turbines were moved to near [[Peterhead]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://syslagronn.no/2017/02/17/syslagronn/na-starter-monteringen-av-statoils-flytende-vindmoller_191270/ |title=Nå starter monteringen av Statoils flytende vindmøller|work=SYSLA |date=17 February 2017|accessdate=20 February 2017}}</ref><ref name=tu2017-02>{{cite web|url= https://www.tu.no/artikler/gigant-moduler-til-verdens-forste-flytende-vindpark-har-ankommet-stordbase/376691 |title=Gigant-moduler til verdens første flytende vindpark har ankommet Stordbase|work=[[Teknisk Ukeblad]] |date=16 February 2017 |accessdate=20 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Floating turbines deliver first electricity|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-41652707|website=BBC News|accessdate=18 October 2017|date=18 October 2017}}</ref> Three [[Suction caisson|suction cup anchors]] hold each turbine.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.tu.no/artikler/sjekk-dimensjonene-disse-kjettingene-skal-feste-statoils-flytende-vindmolle-til-havbunnen/346472 |title=Sjekk dimensjonene: Disse kjettingene skal feste Statoils flytende vindmølle til havbunnen|author=Jannicke Nilsen |work=[[Teknisk Ukeblad]] |accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref>
The first floating turbine in Japan was floated near [[Fukue Island]] in 2016, after a 5-year demonstration period near shore.<ref>[http://www.4coffshore.com/windfarms/japanese-floater-gets-relocated-nid3670.html Japanese floater gets relocated] ''4C'', 21 April 2016</ref> The 2-MW turbine was developed by [[Hitachi]].{{update after|2018|8|3}}
In June 2016, Maine’s New England Aqua Ventus I floating offshore wind demonstration project, designed by the DeepCwind Consortium, was selected by the U.S. Department of Energy to participate in the Offshore Wind Advanced Technology Demonstration program.<ref>{{cite web|title=Maine Offshore Wind Project Moves to Top Tier of National Offshore Wind Demonstration Program|url=https://www.collins.senate.gov/newsroom/maine-offshore-wind-project-moves-top-tier-national-offshore-wind-demonstration-program|website=U.S. Senator Susan Collins|publisher=United States Senate|accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref>{{update after|2018|8|3}}
==Anchoring systems== [[File:Floating tension leg wind turbine diagram.svg|thumb|Left-hand tower-bearing structure (grey) is free floating, the right-hand structure is pulled by the tensioned cables (red) down towards the seabed anchors (light-grey).]] Two common types of engineered design for anchoring floating structures include [[Tension-leg platform|tension-leg]] and [[catenary]] [[Mooring (watercraft)|loose mooring]] systems.{{Citation needed|date=October 2011}}<ref name=jonk/>{{rp|2–4}} ''Tension leg mooring systems'' have vertical tethers under tension providing large restoring [[Moment of inertia|moments]] in [[Roll, pitch, and yaw|pitch]] and [[Flight dynamics|roll]]. ''Catenary mooring systems'' provide station–keeping for an offshore structure yet provide little stiffness at low tensions."<ref name=mit200710>[http://web.mit.edu/flowlab/pdf/Floating_Offshore_Wind_Turbines.pdf Floating Offshore Wind Turbines: Responses in a Seastate -- Pareto Optimal Designs and Economic Assessment], P. Sclavounos et al, October 2007</ref> A third form of mooring system is the ''ballasted catenary'' configuration, created by adding multiple-tonne weights hanging from the midsection of each anchor cable in order to provide additional cable tension and therefore increase stiffness of the above-water floating structure.<ref name=mit200710/>
The [[IEC 61400]]–3 design standard requires that a loads analysis be based on site-specific external conditions such as wind, wave and currents.<ref name=jonk/>{{rp|75}} The IEC 61400–3-2 standard applies specifically to floating wind turbines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iec.ch/dyn/www/f?p=103:38:0::::FSP_ORG_ID,FSP_APEX_PAGE,FSP_LANG_ID,FSP_PROJECT:1282,23,25/,IEC/TS%2061400-3-2%20Ed.%201.0#|title=IEC - TC 88 Dashboard > Projects: Work programme, Publications, Maintenance cycle, Project files, TC/SC in figures|publisher=Iec.ch|date=15 October 2010|accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.veristar.com/content/static/veristarinfo/images/4706.26.572NI_2010-11.pdf | title=Classification and Certification of Floating Offshore Wind Turbines|publisher=Veristar.com|accessdate=2 December 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203004709/http://www.veristar.com/content/static/veristarinfo/images/4706.26.572NI_2010-11.pdf|archivedate=3 December 2013}}</ref>
==Economics== The technical feasibility of deepwater floating wind turbines is not questioned, as the long-term survivability of floating structures has been successfully demonstrated by the marine and [[offshore oil drilling platform|offshore oil industries]] over many decades. However, the economics that allowed the deployment of thousands of offshore oil rigs have yet to be demonstrated for floating wind turbine platforms. For deepwater wind turbines, a floating structure will replace pile-driven monopoles or conventional concrete bases that are commonly used as foundations for shallow water and land-based turbines. The floating structure must provide enough buoyancy to support the weight of the turbine and to restrain pitch, roll and heave motions within acceptable limits. The capital costs for the wind turbine itself will not be significantly higher than current marine-proofed turbine costs in shallow water. Therefore, the economics of deepwater wind turbines will be determined primarily by the additional costs of the floating structure and [[power distribution]] system, which are offset by higher [[wind resource assessment|offshore winds]] and close proximity to large load centres (e.g. shorter transmission runs).<ref name="Musial2003"/>
{{As of|2009}} however, the economic feasibility of [[Shallow-water offshore wind power|shallow-water offshore wind technologies]] is more completely understood. With empirical data obtained from fixed-bottom installations off many countries since the late 1990s, representative costs are well understood. Shallow-water turbines cost between 2.4 and 3&nbsp;million [[United States dollar]]s per megawatt to install, according to the [[World Energy Council]],<ref name="Patel2009">{{cite news|last=Patel|first=Prachi|title=Floating Wind Turbines to Be Tested|work=|publisher=[[IEEE Spectrum]]|date=22 June 2009|url=http://www.spectrum.ieee.org/green-tech/wind/floating-wind-turbines-to-be-tested|accessdate=25 June 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090628200828/http://www.spectrum.ieee.org/green-tech/wind/floating-wind-turbines-to-be-tested|archive-date=28 June 2009|dead-url=yes}}</ref> while the practical feasibility and per-unit economics of deep-water, floating-turbine offshore wind is yet to be established. Initial deployment of single full-capacity turbines in deep-water locations began only in 2009.<ref name="Patel2009"/>
{{as of|2010|10}}, new feasibility studies are supporting that floating turbines are becoming both technically and economically viable in the UK and global energy markets. "The higher up-front costs associated with developing floating wind turbines would be offset by the fact that they would be able to access areas of deep water off the coastline of the UK where winds are stronger and reliable."<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2010/oct/11/floating-turbines-reliable-wind |title=Floating turbines promise to deliver reliable wind, says report &#124; Environment|publisher=theguardian.com|accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> The recent Offshore Valuation study conducted in the UK has confirmed that using just one third of the UK's wind, wave and tidal resource could generate energy equivalent to 1&nbsp;billion barrels of oil per year; the same as North Sea oil and gas production. A significant challenge when using this approach is the coordination needed to develop transmission lines.
A 2015 report by [[Carbon Trust]] recommends 11 ways to reduce cost.<ref>[http://www.carbontrust.com/resources/reports/technology/floating-offshore-wind-market-technology-review/ Floating Offshore Wind Market Technology Review] ''[[Carbon Trust]]''</ref> Also in 2015, researchers at [[University of Stuttgart]] estimated cost at €230/MWh.<ref>https://www.sintef.no/globalassets/project/eera-deepwind-2015/presentations/f/f_matha_univ-stuttgart.pdf</ref>
===Oil well injection=== When [[oil field]]s become depleted, the operator [[Water injection (oil production)|injects water to keep pressure high]] for [[Extraction of petroleum#Secondary recovery|further extraction]]. This requires power, but installing gas turbines means shutting down the extraction process, losing valuable income. The [[classification society]] [[DNV GL]] has calculated that in some cases a floating wind turbine can economically provide power for injection, as the [[oil platform]] can keep on producing, avoiding a costly pause.<ref name=waterin>{{cite web|url= http://www.offshorewind.biz/2016/11/25/in-depth-techtalk-floating-wind-powered-water-injection/ |title= Floating wind-powered water injection|work=Offshore Wind|date=25 November 2016|accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref><ref name=jan>Nilsen, Jannicke. "[http://www.tu.no/kraft/2015/01/20/dnv-gl-na-kan-det-lonne-seg-med-flytende-havvind-til-oljeplattformer DNV GL: Nå kan det lønne seg med flytende havvind til oljeplattformer]" [https://translate.google.dk/translate?sl=no&tl=en&js=y&prev=_t&hl=da&ie=UTF-8&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.tu.no%2Fkraft%2F2015%2F01%2F20%2Fdnv-gl-na-kan-det-lonne-seg-med-flytende-havvind-til-oljeplattformer&edit-text= In English] ''[[Teknisk Ukeblad]]'', 20 January 2015. Accessed: 22 January 2015</ref>
In 2016 DNV GL, [[ExxonMobil]] and others approved calculations of saving $3/[[Barrel of oil equivalent|barrel of oil]] using a 6MW Hywind instead of traditional engines, driving two 2MW pumps injecting water into an [[Offshore drilling|offshore oil well]]. At least 44,000 [[Barrel (unit)#Oil barrel|barrels]] of processed water per day can be injected, even on calm June days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dnvgl.com/news/dnv-gl-led-project-gives-green-light-for-wind-powered-oil-recovery-63901 |title=DNV GL-led project gives green light for wind-powered oil recovery <!--download report-->|work=[[DNV GL]]|accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tu.no/artikler/snart-kan-oljeselskapene-fa-strom-fra-flytende-havvind-kan-spare-3-dollar-fatet/346957 |title=Snart kan oljeselskapene få strøm fra flytende havvind - kan spare 3 dollar fatet|author=Tormod Haugstad|work=[[Teknisk Ukeblad]]|accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://www.rechargenews.com/wind/1431644/win-win-floating-wind-concept-feasible-for-oil-and-gas-developments Win-Win floating wind concept 'feasible' for oil & gas developments] (paywall)</ref> The project began laboratory testing in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.offshorewind.biz/2017/04/19/offshore-wind-powered-oil-recovery-concept-step-closer-to-reality/ |title=Offshore Wind Powered Oil Recovery Concept Step Closer to Reality|publisher=Offshorewind.biz |accessdate=19 April 2017}}</ref>
==Floating wind farms==
The only operational floating wind farm is [[Hywind Scotland]]. The farm has 5 floating turbines with a total capacity of 30 MW.<ref name="cleantechnica.com"/>
===Proposals=== {{As of|2011|09}}, Japan had planned to build a pilot floating wind farm, with six 2-megawatt turbines, off the [[Fukushima Prefecture|Fukushima coast]] of northeast Japan where the [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster|recent disaster]] has created a scarcity of electric power.<ref name=bb20110916>{{cite news|title=Japan Plans Floating Wind Power Plant|url=http://www.breakbulk.com/wind-renewables/japan-plans-floating-wind-power-plant|accessdate=12 October 2011|newspaper=Breakbulk|date=16 September 2011}}</ref><ref>Annette Bossler. "[http://www.windpoweroffshore.com/article/1211680/floating-turbines---japan-enters-stage Floating turbines - Japan enters the stage]" ''OffshoreWind'', 12 September 2013. Accessed: 17 October 2013</ref> After the evaluation phase is complete in 2016, "Japan plans to build as many as 80 floating wind turbines off Fukushima by 2020."<ref name=bb20110916/> The cost is expected to be in the range of 10–20&nbsp;billion Yen over five years to build the first six floating wind turbines.<ref name=reuters20110913>Yoko Kubota [https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/09/13/us-japan-wind-idUSTRE78C41M20110913 Japan plans floating wind power for Fukushima coast] ''[[Reuters]]'', 13 September 2011. Accessed: 19 September 2011</ref> In 2011, some foreign companies had also planned to bid on the 1-GW large floating wind farm that Japan hoped to build by 2020.<ref name=wpm20111101> {{cite news|last=Quilter|first=James|title=Statoil looks to Japan with Hywind concept|url=http://www.windpowermonthly.com/channel/technology/news/1101675/Statoil-looks-Japan-Hywind-concept/|accessdate=1 December 2011|newspaper=WindPower Monthly|date=1 November 2011}}</ref> In March 2012, [[Minister of Economy, Trade and Industry (Japan)|Japan’s Ministry of Economy, Trade and Industry]] approved a 12.5bn yen ($154m) project to float a 2-MW Fuji in March 2013 and two 7-MW Mitsubishi hydraulic "SeaAngel" later about 20–40&nbsp;km offshore in 100–150 metres of water depth. The Japanese Wind Power Association claims a potential of 519&nbsp;GW of floating offshore wind capacity in Japan.<ref name=fuku>Patton, Dominique. [http://www.rechargenews.com/energy/wind/article306702.ece Mitsubishi and Fuji named for Fukushima offshore wind farm] ''Recharge News'', 6 March 2012. Accessed: 8 March 2012</ref> The first turbine became operational in November 2013.<ref>Elaine Kurtenbach. "[http://www.smh.com.au/world/japan-starts-up-offshore-wind-farm-near-fukushima-20131112-2xct0.html Japan starts up offshore wind farm near Fukushima]" [[The Sydney Morning Herald]], 12 November 2013. Accessed: 11 November 2013</ref><ref>"[http://www.offshorewind.biz/2013/10/11/japan-experimental-offshore-floating-wind-farm-project-2/ Japan: Experimental Offshore Floating Wind Farm Project]" ''OffshoreWind'', 11 October 2013. Accessed: 12 October 2013</ref> In 2018, NEDO has announced two tenders to be launched in early February, aiming to support the development of both floating and fixed-bottom offshore wind projects in the country <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.offshorewind.biz/2018/01/12/japan-nedo-takes-further-offshore-wind-steps/.|title=Japan: NEDO Takes Further Offshore Wind Steps|publisher=}}</ref>
The US State of [[Maine]] solicited proposals in September 2010 to build a floating wind farm. The [[RFP]]{{clarify|date=March 2018}} is seeking proposals for 25&nbsp;MW of deep-water offshore wind capacity to supply power for 20-year long-term contract period in the [[Gulf of Maine]]. Proposals were due by May 2011.<ref name=be20100903>[http://www.brighterenergy.org/15782/news/marine-hydro/maine-seeks-30mw-of-offshore-wind-and-tidal-pilots/ Maine seeks 30MW of offshore wind and tidal pilots], ''BrighterEnergy.org'', 3 September 2010, accessed 12 September 2010</ref><ref name=mst20100606>[http://www.pressherald.com/news/the-point-man-on-offshore-wind-clearly-energized_2010-06-06.html State point man on offshore wind clearly energized], ''[[Maine Sunday Telegram]]'', 6 June 2010, accessed 13 June 2010: ''"In September, the state plans to send out bids to build the world's first floating, commercial wind farm off the Maine coast."''</ref> In April 2012 Statoil received state regulatory approval to build a large four-unit demonstration wind farm off the coast of Maine.<ref name=hb20120430>{{cite news|last=Hampton|first=Stuart|title=Statoil to demonstrate floating offshore wind turbines in the US|url=http://bizmology.hoovers.com/2012/04/30/statoil-to-demonstrate-floating-offshore-wind-turbines-in-the-us/|accessdate=20 May 2012|publisher=Hoovers|newspaper=Bizmology|date=30 April 2012|quote=''Statoil has secured the support of government officials in Maine to develop a demonstration wind park in the US with four full-scale offshore wind turbines.''}}</ref> {{asof|2013|04}}, the ''Hywind&nbsp;2'' 4-tower, 12–15&nbsp;MW wind farm was being developed by Statoil North America for placement {{convert|20|km}} off the east coast of [[Maine]] in {{convert|140|-|158|m}}-deep water of the [[Atlantic Ocean]]. Like the first Hywind installation off Norway, the turbine foundation will be a ''spar floater''.<ref name=4cos20140403>{{cite web|title=Hywind 2 Demonstration (Maine)|url=http://www.4coffshore.com/windfarms/hywind-2-demonstration-%28maine%29-united-states-us3b.html|work=Offshore Wind Farms Project Database|publisher=4C Offshore|accessdate=3 April 2013}}</ref> The [[State of Maine]] [[Public Utility Commission]] voted to approve the construction and fund the US$120&nbsp;million project by adding approximately 75&nbsp;cents/month to the average retail electricity consumer. Power could be flowing into the grid no earlier than 2016.<ref name=pph20130125>{{cite news|title=Pioneering Maine wind project passes 'biggest hurdle'|url=http://www.pressherald.com/news/PUC-approves-maine-statoil-wind-turbine-offshore-deepwater.html?pagenum=full|accessdate=3 April 2013|newspaper=Portland Press Herald|date=25 January 2013}}</ref> As a result of [[Maine Legislature|legislation]] in 2013 ([http://www.mainelegislature.org/LawMakerWeb/summary.asp?ID=280048788 LD 1472]) by the [[State of Maine]], [[Statoil]] placed the planned Hywind Maine floating wind turbine development project on hold in July 2013. The legislation required the [[Maine Public Utilities Commission]] to undertake a second round of bidding for the offshore wind sites with a different set of ground rules, which subsequently led Statoil to suspend due to increased uncertainty and risk in the project. Statoil is considering other locations for its initial US demonstration project.<ref name=osw20130705>{{cite news|title=USA: Statoil Freezes Hywind Maine Project|url=http://www.offshorewind.biz/2013/07/05/usa-statoil-freezes-hywind-maine-project/|accessdate=2 August 2013|newspaper=OffshoreWind.biz|date=5 July 2013}}</ref> Some vendors who could bid on the proposed project in Maine expressed concerns in 2010 about dealing with the [[Federal government of the United States|United States]] regulatory environment. Since the proposed site is in [[Outer Continental Shelf|Federal waters]], developers would need a permit from the US [[Minerals Management Service]], "which took more than seven years to approve a [[Cape Wind|yet-to-be-built, shallow-water wind project]] off [[Cape Cod]]". Also, the agency is under fire in June 2010 for lax oversight of deepwater oil drilling in Federal waters. "Uncertainty over regulatory hurdles in the United States … is 'the Achilles heel' for Maine's ambitions for deepwater wind."<ref name=mst20100606/>
==Research== Scale modeling and computer modeling attempt to predict the behavior of large–scale wind turbines in order to avoid costly failures and to expand the use of offshore wind power from fixed to floating foundations. Topics for research in this field include:
===Computer models=== * Overview of integrated dynamic calculations for floating offshore wind turbines<ref name=tools>Andrew Cordle ([[GL Garrad Hassan]]) & Jason Jonkman ([[NREL]]). [http://www.nrel.gov/docs/fy12osti/50543.pdf "State of the Art in Floating Wind Turbine Design Tools"] NREL/CP-5000-50543, ''[[NREL]]'' October 2011. Retrieved 25 June 2012</ref> * Fully coupled aerohydro-servo-elastic response; a basic research tool to validate new designs<ref name=jonk>Jonkman, J.M. [http://www.nrel.gov/docs/fy08osti/41958.pdf "Dynamics Modeling and Loads Analysis of an Offshore Floating Wind Turbine"] Technical Report NREL/TP-500-41958, ''[[NREL]]'' November 2007. Retrieved 25 June 2012<!--numerous references--></ref>
===Scale models=== * Water tank studies on 1:100 scale [[tension-leg platform]] and Spar Buoy platforms<ref name=naqvi>Naqvi, Syed Kazim. [http://www.wpi.edu/Pubs/ETD/Available/etd-052312-133921/unrestricted/knaqvi1.pdf "Scale model experiments on floating offshore wind turbines"] ''[[Worcester Polytechnic Institute]]'', May 2012. Retrieved 25 June 2012</ref> * Dynamic response dependency on the mooring configuration<ref name=groen>[http://www.groendyst.dtu.dk/upload/dtu%20kommunikation/groen_dyst/gd_abstractbog_web.pdf ]{{dead link|date=December 2013}}</ref>{{full citation needed|date=April 2014}}
==Other applications== As they are suitable for towing, floating wind turbine units can be relocated to any location on the sea without much additional cost. So they can be used as prototype test units to practically assess the design adequacy and wind power potential of prospective sites.
When the transmission of generated wind power to nearby land is not economical, the power can be used in [[power to gas]] applications to produce [[hydrogen]] gas, [[ammonia]] / [[urea]], [[reverse osmosis]] water [[desalination]], [[natural gas]], [[Liquefied petroleum gas|LPG]], [[alkylate]] / [[gasoline]], etc. on floating platforms which can be easily transported to nearby consuming centres.<ref>{{cite web|title=Offshore Wind Costs Fall Below New Nuclear Plants in U.K.|url=http://www.eqmagpro.com/offshore-wind-costs-fall-below-new-nuclear-plants-in-u-k/|accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref>
Floating wind turbines can be used to provide motive power for achieving artificial [[upwelling]] of nutrient-rich deep ocean water to the surface for enhancing fisheries growth in areas with tropical and temperate weather.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download;jsessionid=EA65E2A45138AE993750B20FAC628ECC?doi=10.1.1.526.2024&rep=rep1&type=pdf|title=Enhancing fish stocks with artificial upwelling |accessdate=7 May 2017}}</ref> Though deep seawater (below 50 metres depth) is rich in nutrients such as nitrogen and phosphorus, the [[phytoplankton]] growth is poor due to the absence of sunlight. The most productive ocean fishing grounds are located in cold water seas at high latitudes where natural upwelling of deep sea water occurs due to inverse [[thermocline]] temperatures. The electricity generated by the floating wind turbine would be used to drive high–flow and low–head water pumps to draw cold water from below 50 meters water depth and mixed with warm surface water by [[Water eductor|eductors]] before releasing into the sea. [[Mediterranean Sea]], [[Black Sea]], [[Caspian Sea]], [[Red Sea]], [[Persian Gulf]], deep water lakes/reservoirs are suitable for artificial upwelling for enhancing fish catch economically. These units can also be mobile type to utilise the seasonal favourable winds all around the year.
==Floating design concepts==
===DeepWind=== [[Risø DTU National Laboratory for Sustainable Energy|Risø]] and 11 international partners started a 4-year program called DeepWind in October 2010 to create and test economical floating [[Vertical Axis Wind Turbine]]s up to 20&nbsp;MW. The program is supported with [[Euro|€]]3m through [[European Union|EU]]s [[Seventh Framework Programme]].<ref name=ing20101111>{{cite web|last=Stage|first=Mie|title=Risø floats 20MW|url=http://ing.dk/artikel/113908-risoe-dtu-vil-lave-flydende-20-mw-havvindmoeller|language=Danish|publisher=Ingeniøren|date=11 November 2010|accessdate=17 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101114025558/http://ing.dk/artikel/113908-risoe-dtu-vil-lave-flydende-20-mw-havvindmoeller|archive-date=14 November 2010|dead-url=yes}}</ref><ref name="risoDW">[http://www.risoe.dtu.dk/Research/sustainable_energy/wind_energy/projects/VEA_DeepWind.aspx DeepWind] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101111021743/http://www.risoe.dtu.dk/Research/sustainable_energy/wind_energy/projects/VEA_DeepWind.aspx |date=11 November 2010 }} ''[[Risø DTU National Laboratory for Sustainable Energy|Risø]]'', sourcedate. Retrieved: 11 November 2010</ref> Partners include [[Delft University of Technology|TUDelft]], [[Aalborg University]], [[SINTEF]], [[Equinor]] and United States [[National Renewable Energy Laboratory]].<ref name="test">Munck, Susanne. [http://www.risoe.dtu.dk/News_archives/News/2010/1115_DeepWind.aspx?sc_lang=da Future turbines] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101115124937/http://www.risoe.dtu.dk/News_archives/News/2010/1115_DeepWind.aspx?sc_lang=da |date=15 November 2010 }} ''[[Risø DTU National Laboratory for Sustainable Energy|Risø]]'', Danish, 8 November 2010. Retrieved: 11 November 2010</ref>
===GICON=== The GICON-TLP is a floating substructure system based on a tension leg platform (TLP) developed by GICON GmbH.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gicon-sof.de/en/sof1.html|title=Home: Das GICON®-SOF Schwimmendes Offshorefundament|website=www.gicon-sof.de}}</ref> The system is deployable from 45 meters to 350 meters water depth. It consists of six major components: four buoyancy bodies, horizontal pipes for structural base, vertical pipes which pass through the water line, angled piles for connection with the transition piece. Casted nodes are used to connect all components. The TLP can be equipped with an offshore wind turbine in range of 6–10 MW.
The GICON-TLP is anchored to the seabed via four pre-tensioned mooring ropes with a buoyant gravity-base anchor consisting of concrete. No pile driving or drilling for anchoring is necessary. All ropes are connected at the corners of the square based system. The TLP for a 6MW wind turbine is currently being developed by the GICON Group and their key partner, the Endowed Chair for Wind Energy Technology (LWET) at the University of Rostock, utilizing prefabricated steel-concrete composite components in combination with components of steel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lwet.uni-rostock.de/en/research/design-concepts-for-wind-turbines/third-generation-floating-offshore-foundation-sof-3/|title=Third-Generation Floating Offshore Foundation (SOF-3) - Stiftungslehrstuhl für Windenergietechnik - Universität Rostock|website=www.lwet.uni-rostock.de}}</ref> A main focus of the TLP design is on the modularity and the possibility of assembly in any dry dock near to the installation site and without the use of construction vessels.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-nLjeSqaER0|title=Transport und Installation GICON®-SOF mit Fundament und Schwergewichtsanker|first=|last=GICON Firmengruppe|date=21 August 2015|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>Frank Adam u. a.: Entwicklung eines Fundaments für Offshore-Windenergieanlagen aus Stahl-Beton-Verbundbauteilen. In: Schiff & Hafen. Heft 11/2016, S. 40–43, ISSN 0938-1643</ref> After offshore location is reached, joints of TLP and anchor will be decoupled and the gravity anchor will be lowered down by using ballast water. Once the anchor has reached the bottom, it is filled with sand. One unique feature of the system is the sufficient floating stability during transport as well as during operations.
In October 2017, model tests took place in the model test facility of French École Centrale de Nantes (ECN) with 1:50 model of the GICON®-TLP incl. wind turbine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.offshorewind.biz/2017/11/10/gicon-floater-passes-first-tank-test-video/?uid=59262|title=Gicon Floater Passes First Tank Test (VIDEO)|publisher=}}</ref> Based on this test a TRL of 5 was reached.
===Ideol=== [[File:Floater fully coated hires.jpg|alt=|thumb|Steel floating substructure designed by Ideol for 3.2 MW NEDO project (Japan) based on Ideol technology, fully coated in dry dock before wind turbine installation]] [[File:Floatgen.jpg|thumb|left|Ideol's 2MW floating wind turbine installed off France ]] Ideol’s engineers have developed and patented a ring-shaped floating foundation based on a central opening system (Damping Pool) used for optimizing foundation + wind turbine stability. As such, the sloshing water contained in this central opening counteracts the swell-induced floater oscillations. Foundation-fastened mooring lines are simply attached to the seabed to hold the assembly in position. This floating foundation is compatible with all wind turbines without any modification and has reduced dimensions (from 36 to 55 metres per side for a wind turbine between 2 and 8 MW). Manufacturable in concrete or steel, this floating foundation allows for local construction near project sites. Ideol leads the FLOATGEN project, a floating wind turbine demonstration project based on Ideol’s technology, built by Bouygues Travaux Publics and to be installed off the coast of Le Croisic on the offshore experimentation site of Ecole Centrale de Nantes (SEM-REV). The construction of this project, France's first offshore wind turbine (precisely 2 MW), is completed and the floating wind turbine was installed in April 2018.
In June 2015, the company has sealed its first commercial contract with the Japanese conglomerate Hitachi Zosen, for the design of the two latest Japanese floating offshore wind demonstrators.<ref>http://renews.biz/85423/french-help-japan-with-floaters/</ref> In July 2016, Ideol and Hitachi Zosen have signed a contract launching the construction phase of their 2 floating offshore wind turbines. Construction of the first one, manufactured in steel, is completed in dry dock and due to be commissioned before September 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rechargenews.com/wind/1511342/steel-ideol-floating-wind-unit-ready-for-tow-out-off-japan|title=Steel Ideol floating wind unit ready for tow-out off Ja|date=13 June 2018|work=Recharge {{!}} Renewable energy news and articles|access-date=19 June 2018|language=en}}</ref>
In August 2017, the French government has selected Eolmed, a consortium led by Quadran in association with Ideol, Bouygues Travaux Publics and Senvion, a French renewable energy developer, for the development and construction of a 25MW Mediterranean floating offshore wind farm 15&nbsp;km off the coastal town of Gruissan (Languedoc-Roussillon), planned to be commissioned 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.offshorewind.biz/2016/07/25/senvion-turbines-to-float-off-french-mediterranean-coast/|title=Senvion Turbines to Float off French Mediterranean Coast|work=Offshore Wind|accessdate=1 August 2016}}</ref>
===Nautica Windpower=== Nautica Windpower has proposed a technique for potentially reducing system weight, complexity and costs for deepwater sites. Scale model tests in open water have been conducted (September 2007) in Lake Erie and structural dynamics modeling was done in 2010 for larger designs.<ref name="LudingtonDailyNews2010">{{cite web|last=Braciszeski |first=Kevin |title=Why Not Floating Windmills? |publisher=Ludington Daily News |date=23 January 2010 |url=http://www.ludingtondailynews.com/news/47569-why-not-floating-windmills |accessdate=8 February 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714000645/http://www.ludingtondailynews.com/news/47569-why-not-floating-windmills |archivedate=14 July 2011 }}</ref> Nautica Windpower's Advanced Floating Turbine (AFT) uses a single mooring line and a downwind two-bladed rotor configuration that is deflection tolerant and aligns itself with the wind without an active yaw system. Two-bladed, downwind turbine designs that can accommodate flexibility in the blades will potentially prolong blade lifetime, diminish structural system loads and reduce offshore maintenance needs, yielding lower lifecycle costs.<ref name="USOWC2009">{{cite web|title=US Offshore Wind Energy: A Path Forward|work=Working Paper page 24|publisher=US Offshore Wind Collaborative|date=16 October 2009|url=http://www.usowc.org/pdfs/PathForwardfinal.pdf|accessdate=7 November 2009}}</ref>
===SeaTwirl=== SeaTwirl develops a floating vertical axis wind turbine (VAWT). The floater is based on a SPAR solution and is rotating along with the turbine. The concept limits the need for moving parts as well as bearings in the hub region. SeaTwirl is based in Gothenburg Sweden and is registered on the European growth market First North. 2015 SeaTwirl launched a 30kW prototype in the archipelago of Sweden which is connected to the grid at Lysekil. The aim is to scale the concept and to prove the scalability with a turbine of 1MW size in 2020. The concept is scalable for sizes well over 10MW.
===VolturnUS === [[File:VolturnUS 1-8 in Castine ME.jpg|thumb|The VolturnUS design utilizes a concrete semi-submersible floating hull and a composite materials tower designed to reduce both capital and Operation & Maintenance costs, and to allow local manufacturing.]] VolturnUS is North America’s first floating grid-connected wind turbine. It was lowered into the [[Penobscot River]] in [[Maine]] on 31 May 2013 by the [[UMaine Advanced Structures and Composites Center|University of Maine Advanced Structures and Composites Center]] and its partners.<ref>{{cite web|last=Danko|first=Pete|url=http://www.earthtechling.com/2013/05/maine-floating-turbine-in-the-water/|title=First US Floating Wind Turbine Launches In Maine|publisher=EarthTechling|accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nature.com/news/renewable-energy-wind-power-tests-the-waters-1.15992|title=Renewable energy: Wind power tests the waters|work=Nature News & Comment}}</ref> During its deployment, it experienced numerous storm events representative of design environmental conditions prescribed by the American Bureau of Shipping (ABS) Guide for Building and Classing Floating Offshore Wind Turbines, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=VolturnUS 1:8|url=http://composites.umaine.edu/our-research/volturnus/|website=UMaine Advanced Structures and Composites Center|publisher=University of Maine|accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref>
The VolturnUS floating concrete hull technology can support wind turbines in water depths of 45 m or more. With 12 independent cost estimates from around the U.S. and the world, it has been found to significantly reduce costs compared to existing floating systems. The design has also received a complete third-party engineering review.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://composites.umaine.edu/2016/05/30/new-england-aqua-ventus-i-selected-by-the-doe-for-additional-funding/|title=New England Aqua Ventus I Selected by the DOE for up to $39.9 Million in Additional Funding {{!}} Advanced Structures & Composites Center {{!}} University of Maine|website=composites.umaine.edu|access-date=5 July 2016|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160719035555/http://composites.umaine.edu/2016/05/30/new-england-aqua-ventus-i-selected-by-the-doe-for-additional-funding/|archivedate=19 July 2016}}</ref>
In June 2016, the UMaine-led New England Aqua Ventus I project won top tier status from the US Department of Energy (DOE) Advanced Technology Demonstration Program for Offshore Wind. This means that the Aqua Ventus project is now automatically eligible for an additional $39.9 Million in construction funding from the DOE, as long as the project continues to meet its milestones.
===WindFloat=== {{external media |align=right | video1 =[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IO7GXLR4YUo A video describing the WindFloat.]}} [[File:Diagram of Principle Power's WindFloat.jpg|upright|thumb|A diagram of the WindFloat system.]] WindFloat is a floating foundation for offshore [[wind turbine]]s designed and patented by [[Principle Power]]. A full-scale prototype was constructed in 2011 by Windplus, a joint-venture between [[Energias de Portugal|EDP]], [[Repsol]], Principle Power, A. Silva Matos, Inovcapital, and FAI.<ref name=bgWP/> The complete system was assembled and commissioned onshore including the turbine. The entire structure was then wet-towed {{convert|400|km}} (from southern to northern Portugal) to its final installed location {{convert|5|km}} offshore of Aguçadoura, [[Portugal]], previously the [[Aguçadoura Wave Farm]]. The WindFloat was equipped with a [[Vestas]] v80 2.0-megawatt turbine<ref name="ctWP">Shahan, Zachary. [http://cleantechnica.com/2011/02/23/1st-of-its-kind-floating-wind-turbine-technology-to-be-deployed-by-vestas-windplus-video/ 1st-of-its-kind floating wind turbine technology to be deployed by Vestas & WindPlus] ''Clean Technica'', 23 February 2011. Accessed: 23 February 2011</ref> and installation was completed on 22 October 2011. A year later, the turbine had produced 3&nbsp;GWh.<ref>{{cite web|last=Snieckus|first=Darius |title=Principle Power lands $43m funding double for WindFloat|url= http://www.rechargenews.com/energy/wind/article329608.ece |publisher=RechargeNews|accessdate=21 December 2012|date=18 December 2012}}</ref><!--capfac 17%--> The cost of this project is around €20 million (about US $26 million). This single wind turbine can produce energy to power 1300 homes.<ref name="REPORTAGEM_EXPRESSO">{{cite web|title=Principle Power & EDP to Develop Floating Offshore Wind|publisher=expresso.sapo.pt |date=28 February 2013|url=https://expresso.sapo.pt/eolica-mundial-inaugurada-em-agucadoura=f734388 |accessdate=28 February 2013}}</ref>
The subsea metal structure is reported to improve dynamic stability, whilst still maintaining shallow [[draft (hull)|draft]],<ref name=bgWP>Shankleman, Jessica. [http://www.businessgreen.com/bg/news/2027483/vestas-floats-plan-windplus-offshore-demo Vestas floats plan for WindPlus offshore demo] ''Business Green'', 18 February 2011. Accessed: 23 February 2011</ref> by dampening wave– and turbine–induced motion<ref name=cwWP>{{cite web|url=http://www.compositesworld.com/news/vestas-windplus-to-deploy-floating-wind-turbine-structure|title=Vestas, WindPlus to deploy floating wind turbine structure|publisher=Composites World|date=21 February 2011|accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> utilizing a tri-column triangular [[offshore platform|platform]] with the wind turbine positioned on one of the three columns. The triangular platform is then "moored" using a conventional [[catenary]] mooring consisting of four lines, two of which are connected to the column supporting the turbine, thus creating an "asymmetric mooring."<ref name="REW200812">{{cite news|last=Balogh|first=Emily |title=Deepwater Offshore Wind Power Generation Using Oil and Gas Platform Technology |publisher=RenewableEnergyWorld.com |date=18 December 2008|url= http://www.renewableenergyworld.com/rea/news/article/2008/12/deepwater-offshore-wind-power-generation-using-oil-and-gas-platform-technology-54314 |accessdate=3 September 2009}}</ref> As the wind shifts direction and changes the loads on the turbine and foundation, a secondary hull-trim system shifts ballast water between each of the three columns.<ref name=ingWP>Rasmussen, Daniel. [http://ing.dk/artikel/116682-vestas-i-forsoeg-om-flydende-havvindmoeller Vestas in experiment with floating wind turbine] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110224035151/http://ing.dk/artikel/116682-vestas-i-forsoeg-om-flydende-havvindmoeller |date=24 February 2011 }} (in Danish). Source: ''Ing.dk'', 21 February 2011. Accessed: 22 February 2011 ''"When the wind turns, the platform is kept level by pumping more water into one of the three cylinders."''</ref> This permits the platform to maintain even keel while producing the maximum amount of energy. This is in contrast to other floating concepts which have implemented control strategies that de-power the turbine to compensate for changes in turbine thrust-induced overturning moment.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}} This technology could allow wind turbines to be sited in offshore areas that were previously considered inaccessible, areas having water depth exceeding 40 m and more powerful wind resources than shallow-water offshore wind farms typically encounter.<ref name="REW200902">{{cite news|title=Principle Power & EDP to Develop Floating Offshore Wind |publisher=RenewableEnergyWorld.com |date=20 February 2009|url= http://www.renewableenergyworld.com/rea/news/article/2009/02/principle-power-edp-sign-moa-for-offshore-wind |accessdate=3 September 2009}}</ref>
A 25 MW WindFloat project received government permission in December 2016, with EU funding the €48 million transmission cable. The €100 million project is expected to be funded by 2017 and operational by 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.windpoweroffshore.com/article/1419415/windfloat-gets-green-light |title=WindFloat gets the green light|publisher=|accessdate=7 January 2017}}</ref> Principle Power was planning a 30-MW WindFloat project using 6-MW Siemens turbines in 366 m of water near [[Coos Bay, Oregon]] to be operational in 2017,<ref>Ros Davidson. "[http://www.windpoweroffshore.com/article/1216167/analysis---floating-turbines-planned-us-west-coast?HAYILC=TOPIC Floating turbines planned for US west coast]" ''Windpower Offshore'', 14 October 2013. Accessed: 23 November 2013</ref> but the project has since been cancelled.<ref>WindFloat Pacific - Offshore Wind Pilot Project "[https://www.boem.gov/windfloatpacific/]"</ref>
===Others=== A combined floating [[Wave power|wave]] and wind power plant was installed at [[Vindeby Offshore Wind Farm]] in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ing.dk/artikel/verdens-forste-kombinerede-bolge-og-vindkraftanlaeg-sosat-109868|title=Verdens første kombinerede bølge- og vindkraftanlæg søsat |date=22 June 2010|publisher=[[Ingeniøren]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tidalenergytoday.com/2016/11/08/dp-energy-fpp-join-hands-for-uks-winds-and-waves/ |title=DP Energy, FPP join hands for UK’s winds and waves|work=Tidal Energy Today| date=8 November 2016|accessdate=24 November 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://www.marinet.eu/public/docs/FPP%20MARINET%20Official%20Report%20for%20ECN%20Tests_FPPHybVal.pdf Joint Wind Wave Testing and Validation of Floating Power Plant’s Renewable Hybrid] ''Marine Renewables Infrastructure Network'', 20 January 2015</ref>
An [[open source]] project was proposed by former Siemens director [[Henrik Stiesdal]] in 2015 to be assessed by [[DNV GL]]. It suggests using tension leg platforms with replaceable pressurized tanks anchored to [[sheet wall]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ing.dk/artikel/vindmoellepioner-open-source-tilgang-kan-give-foererposition-paa-havmoellefundamenter-178927|title=Vindmøllepioner: ’Open source’-tilgang kan give førerposition på havmøllefundamenter|work=[[Ingeniøren]]|trans-title='Open source' approach can provide leadership in offshore foundations}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.dk/translate?sl=da&tl=en&js=y&prev=_t&hl=da&ie=UTF-8&u=http://ing.dk/artikel/vindmoellepioner-open-source-tilgang-kan-give-foererposition-paa-havmoellefundamenter-178927&edit-text=|title=Google Oversæt|website=translate.google.dk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rechargenews.com/wind/1411882/wind-maverick-stiesdal-launches-cost-slashing-floating-foundation-design|title=Wind maverick Stiesdal launches cost-slashing floating foundation design|work=rechargenews.com}}</ref>
The [[International Energy Agency]] (IEA), under the auspices of their ''Offshore Code Comparison Collaboration'' (OC3) initiative, has completed high-level design and [[simulator|simulation modeling]] of the ''OC-3 Hywind'' system, a 5-MW wind turbine installed on a floating [[spar buoy]], moored with catenary mooring lines, in water depth of 320 metres. The spar buoy platform would extend 120 metres below the surface and the mass of such a system, including [[Sailing ballast|ballast]] would exceed 7.4&nbsp;million&nbsp;kg.<ref name=ewec201004>[http://www.ewec2010proceedings.info/papers/1251584258.pdf Offshore Code Comparison Collaboration within IEA Wind Task 23: Phase IV Results Regarding Floating Wind Turbine Modeling], 2010 European Wind Energy Conference (EWEC), 20–23 April 2010, Warsaw, Poland, accessed 11 September 2010</ref>
VertiWind is a floating [[vertical axis wind turbine]] design created by Nenuphar <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nenuphar-wind.com/|title=Nenuphar :: Accueil|publisher=Nenuphar-wind.com|accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref>{{full citation needed|date=November 2012}} whose mooring system and floater are designed by Technip.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.technip.com/|title=Technip|accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> {{full citation needed|date=November 2012}}{{primary source inline|date=August 2013}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sintef.no/project/DeepWind%202013/Deepwind%20presentations%202013/Posters/Antonutti_poster.pdf/|title=Numerical Study on the Motions of the VertiWind Floating Offshore Wind Turbine|accessdate=10 December 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214044720/http://www.sintef.no/project/DeepWind%202013/Deepwind%20presentations%202013/Posters/Antonutti_poster.pdf/|archivedate=14 December 2013}}</ref>
