[[File:Graphen.jpg|thumb|300px|Graphene is an [[Chicken wire (chemistry)|atomic-scale honeycomb lattice]] made of carbon atoms.]] '''GraphExeter''' is a material consisting of a few [[graphene]] sheets with a layer of [[ferric chloride]] molecules in between each graphene sheet.<ref name="BBC">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-18302843 Exeter scientists make 'electric cloth' GraphExeter]</ref><ref name="Novel Devices Exeter">{{cite journal|last=Khrapach|first=Ivan|author2=Freddie Withers |author3=Thomas H. Bointon |author4=Dmitry K. Polyushkin |author5=William L. Barnes |author6=Saverio Russo |author7=Monica F. Craciun |title=Novel highly conductive and transparent graphene-based conductors|journal=Advanced Materials|year=2012|volume=24|issue=21|pages=2844–9|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/adma.201200489/abstract?systemMessage=Wiley+Online+Library+will+be+disrupted+on+23+February+from+10%3A00-12%3A00+BST+%2805%3A00-07%3A00+EDT%29+for+essential+maintenance&userIsAuthenticated=false&deniedAccessCustomisedMessage=|accessdate=July 13, 2012 |doi=10.1002/adma.201200489|arxiv=1206.0001}}</ref> It was created by The Centre for Graphene Science at the [[University of Exeter]] in collaboration with the [[University of Bath]].<ref name="exeter">[http://www.exeter.ac.uk/news/featurednews/title_206443_en.html New graphene-based material could revolutionise electronics industry]</ref>
